comment_data.body:
Inspection doesn't rerun when IDE understands that .packages file has been updated. Need to fix.

Probably smth changed in platform since this inspection appeared, I'm pretty sure it worked previously.

So this is a platform bug?  Thanks for clarifying that.

@alexander-doroshko : if you find a tracking bug, maybe link here?
In the meantime, since this is pretty frustrating for new users especially, is there any way to dismiss or force an inspection to re-run?
Need to think about a fix at Dart plugin level. BTW it looks flaky. Sometimes I can't reproduce the problem.

FWIW this problem changes a bit if we transition to using an editor notification instead (#670).

@alexander-doroshko : is the flakiness that the timestamps are lagging or that the inspection doesn't get re-run?
Inspection. But it could be fixable at plugin end, not in platform.

While the underlying problem doesn't appear to have gone away, https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/commit/75ee5755fd1d5c10764f02200d51e1f18f335aba effectively works around it.  Optimistically closing.

@pq I'm currently experiencing this with a plain dart project (no flutter) in IntelliJ 2019.3.1. Manually opening the ".packages" file resolves the issue. Can your fix be applied to vanilla dart projects too?

Hi @Lootwig.

I'll defer to @alexander-doroshko on whether this should make it's way into the Dart plugin or if there's a better approach.

Sorry for the trouble!
I'm afraid I can't reproduce it.

title: Out of date pubspec inspection lags behind local filesystem changes.
